{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> δεινός</b>, ή, όν, <br /> (δέος,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Laches” 198b)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <b>fearful, terrible;</b> in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], of persons and things, Χάρυβδις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 12.260; κλαγγή 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.49; ὅπλα 10.254: frequently in _neuter_, δεινὸν ἀῧσαι 11.10; βροντᾶν 20.56; δεινὸν δέρκεσθαι 3.342; παπταίνειν 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.608; δεινὰ δ᾽ ὑποδρὰ ἰδών 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.13 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; δ. ἰδέσθαι <b>fearful</b> to behold, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 22.405; δ. μὲν ὁρᾶν, δ. δὲ κλύειν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 141; εἰ καὶ δεινόν τῳ ἀκοῦσαι 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.122; δεινὴ παρὰ τοῖς εἰδόσιν ἡ βάσανος 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.30 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; in milder sense, <b>awful,</b> δεινή τε καὶ αἰδοίη θεός [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 18.394, compare 3.172, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.22, etc.; τὸ δεινόν \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<b>danger, suffering, horror,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 634, etc.\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; <b>awe, terror,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Eu.” 517; ὅπου τὸ δ. ἐλπὶς οὐδὲν ὠφελεῖ 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 196; πρὸς τὸ δ. ἔρχεσθαι [prev. work] 351: in _plural_, ἐκτὸς ὄντα πημάτων τὰ δείν᾽ ὁρᾶν [prev. author] “Ph.” 504; εἰ δείν᾽ ἔδρασας, δεινὰ καὶ παθεῖν σε δεῖ [prev. author] “fragment” 962, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δεινὸν γίγνεται μή.. there is <b>danger</b> that.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.157 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οὐδὲν δεινοὶ ἔσονται μὴ ἀποστέωσιν no <b>fear</b> of their revolting, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 1.155, etc.\">Refs</a>]; δεινότατον μή.. the <b>greatest danger</b> lest.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 3.1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δεινόν ἐστι, with <i>infinitive</i>, it is <b>dangerous</b> to do, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 12.87 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δεινὸν ποιεῖσθαι <b>take ill, complain of, be indignant at</b> a thing: <i>absolutely</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.102, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>infinitive</i>, ὑπὸ Μήδων ἄρχεσθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.127, etc.; also δεινὰ ποιεῖν \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<b>make complaints,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 3.14, 5.41; ἐν δεινῷ τίθεσθαι 1st c.AD: Josephus Historicus “Antiquitates Judaicae” 18.9.8; δεινόν τι ἔσχε αὐτὸν ἀτιμάζεσθαι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.61 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δεινὸν or δεινὰ παθεῖν suffer <b>illegal, arbitrary</b> treatment, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 252, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 317b, etc.; δεινότερα π. 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.13; τὸ δ. τὸ πείσομαι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.11: in Oratt., δεινὸν ἂν εἴη εἰ.. 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.30, 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 12.88, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <i>adverb</i> -νῶς, φέρειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.121 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]. γ; δ. καὶ ἀπόρως ἔχει μοι I am in <b>dire</b> straits, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 1.1; δ. ἔχειν τῇ ἐνδείᾳ 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 6.4.23; δ. διατεθῆναι τυπτόμενος 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 3.27. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>marvellously strong, powerful</b>: δ. σάκος the <b>mighty</b> shield, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.245 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; simply, <b>wondrous, marvellous, strange,</b> τὸ συγγενές τοι δεινὸν ἥ θ᾽ ὁμιλία kin and social ties <b>have strange power,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 39; δ. τὸ κοινὸν σπλάγχνον [prev. author] “Th.” 1036; δ. τὸ τίκτειν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 770; πολλὰ τὰ δ. κοὐδὲν ἀνθρώπου -ότερον πέλει. [prev. author] “Ant.” 333 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δ. ἵμερος, ἔρως, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.3, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 169c; οἶκτος 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 298, etc.; δ. λέγεις πρᾶγμα 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthydemus” 298c; δ. γ᾽ εἶπας, εἰ καὶ ζῇς θανών 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 1127 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; frequently δεινὸν ἂν εἴη εἰ.. it were <b>strange</b> that.., as [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 592. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <i>adverb</i> -νῶς <b>marvellously, exceedingly,</b> δ. μέλαινα, ἄνυδρος, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.76, 149; δ. ἐν φυλακῇσι εἶναι [prev. author] 3.152; δ. πώς εἰμ᾽ ἐπιλήσμων 5th c.BC: Metagenes Comicus 2, etc.: _comparative_ -οτέρως Scholia Min. 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.97. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <b>clever, skilful,</b> first in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.23 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] ἀνὴρ δ. τε καὶ σοφό; of Odysseus, γλώσσῃ.. δεινοῦ καὶ σοφοῦ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 440, compare “OC” 806, 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 2.2.3, 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 7.12; σοφὸς καὶ δ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 341a \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to σοφός, of <b>practical ability,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Phdr.” 245c, “Tht.” 164d \">Refs</a>]; opposed to ἰδιώτης, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 4.35 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>infinitive</i>, δεινὸς εὑρεῖν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 59; δεινοὶ πλέκειν τοι μηχανὰς Αἰγύπτιοι [prev. author] “fragment” 373 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; δ. λέγειν <b>clever</b> at speaking, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 545, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δ. εἰπεῖν is rare, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 20.150; νόσος δ. φαγεῖν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 243; δ. πράγμασι χρῆσθαι 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 1.3 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; αἱ εὐπραξίαι δ. συγκρύψαι τὰ ὀνείδη are <b>wonderfully liable</b> to.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 2.20: with _accusative_, δ. τὴν τέχνην 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 364; δ. περὶ τοὺς λόγους τοὺς εἰς τὰ δικαστήρια 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthydemus” 304d; ἐς τὰ πάντα 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 968 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δ. περὶ τὸ ἀδικεῖν, περὶ Ὁμήρου, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 405c, “Ion” 531a; δ. ἀμφί τι 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Tactica” 9.5; δ. κατὰ χειρουργίαν 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “Varia Historia” 3.1; ἐν λόγοισι δ. Ὑπερείδης 4th c.BC: Timocles Comicus 4.7 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] (but also of the <b>forcible, vehement,</b> style in oratory, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demetrius Phalereus Rhetor “Demetrius on Style” 240, +others)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; in bad sense, <b>over-clever,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthyphro” 3c; δ. ὑπὸ πανουργίας [prev. author] “Tht.” 176d, compare 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1144a27. (For δϝεινός, compare Δϝενία, _genitive_ of _proper name_ Δεινίας, “IG” 4.858.) \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G6791","accentedUnicode":"δεινός","shortDef":"awful","mediumDef":"awful","stepGloss":"awful","stepTransliteration":"deinos","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}